did.unittitle: Rick Lang photographs of Florida and other Southern states

physdesc.physfacet: 229 photographic prints; 258 contact sheets; approximately 3100 negatives; approximately 40 printed items; 130 digital files

did.abstract: Photographer and faculty member at the Creadlé School of Art, Winter Park, Florida. Collection comprises 229 large-format black-and-white photographs by Rick Lang, documenting the communities and landscapes of the American South, with an emphasis on roadside signs, small businesses, and weathered buildings. While the majority of the images were taken in Florida, there also many taken in other states throughout the South, particularly in Louisiana. There are also a few from New Mexico and Arizona. Photographic processes include gelatin silver and pigmented inkjet prints. Print sizes are chiefly 11x14, 13x19, and 16x20 inches, and were printed and signed by the photographer. Accompanying the prints are approximately 3100 negatives and 258 contact sheets linked by unique identification numbers. In addition there is a small amount of print materials chiefly associated with his solo and group exhibits, and condolences sent upon his passing in 2013. Also includes digital files of images. Acquired as part of the Archive of Documentary Arts at Duke University.

arrangement.head: Arrangement

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Rick Lang was a photographer and long-time faculty member of the Crealdé School of Art in Winter Park Florida, a community-based nonprofit arts organization established in 1975.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Collection contains 229 black-and-white gelatin silver or inkjet large-format prints by photographer Rick Lang, documenting the communities and landscapes of Florida and other Southern states; there are also a few images taken in New Mexico and Arizona. Prints are typically sized 11x14, 13x19, and 16x20 inches, and are signed and printed by Lang. About half are housed in 16x20 and 20x24 inch window mats. The prints are arranged in number sequence as assigned by Lang; the negatives and contact sheets are linked by contact sheet numbers which are noted in each print entry in this collection guide.

Lang's work focuses chiefly on scenes of weathered buildings and businesses - stores, motels, bars, alligator farms, and tourist shops - along the back roads of the South; there are also many photographs of signs and graffiti. Few if any people are present. Among the exceptions is a sequence of images of protesters in Florida demonstrating against censorship and other issues.

Accompanying the prints is a full set of negatives and contact sheets, with many additional images that are not present in the large-format series. There is also a small amount of printed materials chiefly associated with his solo and group exhibits, and condolences sent upon his passing in 2013. Three photograph books offer images not present in this collection of people in the Florida communities where Lang lived and worked. Also includes digital files of about 111 selected images.
Acquired as part of the Archive of Documentary Arts at Duke University.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Prints are arranged in their original order according to the numerical sequence applied by the photographer. The print number of each print forms part of the institutional identifier.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Traditional gelatin silver prints are sized either 11x14 (boxes 1-3, matted prints) or 16x20 inches (box 4, matted prints), while the digital inkjet prints are 13x19 inches (boxes 5-6, unmatted). Most of the prints are in 16x20 or 20x24 inch window mats. Sizes in boxes 7-8 are a mix of 11x14 or 16x20 inches - most are matted. Print number 215 is not present in collection and is not present in one version of photographer's inventory.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series contains contact sheets created from original negatives, typically bearing 14-15 black-and-white images. Contact sheet 258 is not present in the collection; however, the corresponding images are available in the negatives series. The total number of images available from the contact sheets is roughly 3500.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Original negatives are closed to general use; access available only by permission of the curator for the Archive of Documentary Arts.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The negatives are arranged in groups corresponding to the contact sheet content and numbering. The majority are 35mm, but there are also a few 128mm and a few 4x5 inch sizes. Negatives from contact sheet 258, which is not present in collection, are available in this series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series includes photography publications, articles, publicity, and obituaries, assembled by Rick Lang's colleague and Executive Director of the Creadlé School of Art in Winter Park, Florida, Peter Schreyer. Three photo books and exhibit catalogues offer many images by Lang not found in this collection's prints, particularly portraits of central Florida people by Lang and other photographers. One exhibition poster is filed in box 5.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Publications with work by Rick Lang. in addition to two magazine articles, includes a set of three soft-cover photography books and exhibit catalogues documenting central Florida communities, featuring work by Rick Lang and others; here one can find Lang's many portraits of Floridians, most of which are not present in the collection as finished prints.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Folder houses exhibit flyers, brochures, and articles about Rick Lang and his photographic work.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Folder of materials includes a message from Excecutive Director Peter Schreyer to the faculty and artists of Creadlé School of Art, where Rick Lang taught, on Lang's death, July 9, 2013. Accompanied by a photocopy of the obituary from the Orlando Sentinel, and condolence and tribute emails from colleagues and friends.
